Most expensive meal I've paid for 2 and it was definitely a delicious meal! About $260 for 2 4 course tasting menu. I came here to celebrate my 2 year anniversary with my girlfriend. They let you do 3, 4, 5 tasting course menu. What that means is you get to pick 3, 4, 5 dishes and they can be from any part of the menu. Heck... you can get all 3,4,5 desserts if you want to as well. Please make reservations at least 1.5 months ahead of time. I tried getting a reservation 1 month in advance and was barely able to get a sunday night 10pm for the weekend! Employees are very nice and they like to focus on the experience while you are there. This place is a must for couples that are into the fine dining experience. They have plenty of unique dishes for you to try out. I've been to a lot of expensive places and they can get boring with your regular surf and turf or steak dish. Coming here, I definitely took the time to go for dishes that caught my eye and certainly my GF LOVED this place. She told me this place was the best restaurant she's been to and she's a big foodie. I know this review has nothing to do with the food. Honestly, I planned my 2 year anniversary 2 months in advanced and tried to find the best place in SF and all other yelp reviews would direct me to Gary Danko. Thanks YELP!

I'm so sad that I can't give Gary Danko a 5-star review. It used to be my favorite restaurant in SF. We went on a Sunday night. I had wanted a Saturday night but I forgot to call exactly 2 months prior and by the time I remembered, it was the day after and there was nothing available for the Saturday. I've heard that Sundays and Mondays are bad nights to have dinner out because the experienced kitchen & wait staff usually take those nights off and it appeared to be the case on our visit. We hit Golden Gate bridge traffic and arrived 15 minutes late. Within 5 minutes of our arrival, while we were still looking at our menu, the amuse bouche was delivered. I thought it was because we were late but it appeared to be the norm since all others in the dining room experienced the same. I balanced the menu on my lap while I had the Curried Carrot Soup with Cumin. This was way too salty and the cumin competed with the curry. I chose the 3-course dinner for $76 and started with Risotto with Lobster, Gulf Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms and Butternut Squash. It was truffle season and you could add 1 gram of shaved black truffle for $20 or 1 gram of shaved white truffle for $25. Based on our trip to the truffle festival in Alba, I knew that the white truffle was more flavorful so I went for it. The truffle looked beautiful but unfortunately there was no truffle smell or taste. It was disappointing. The risotto was well made and al dente though. My next course was the Branzini with Fennel Puree, Nicoise Olives and Saffron-Orange Emulsion. The Branzini was well made. The flesh was soft and the skin was crisp. The fennel puree had no fennel flavor though--it was more like green mashed potato. The saffron-orange emulsion was very mild and not memorable. My last course was Venison with Red Cabbage and Herb Spaetzle. The venison was dry but the cabbage did have good flavor. My husband had the 4-course dinner for $94. He started with Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing. The dressing was too tart--too much lemon. His fish course was the Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon. The lobster was perfectly cooked but there was not much flavor to it. His next course was Veal with Veal Sweetbread. My husband ordered the dish because he loves sweetbread but the sweetbread was a very small piece. The most disappointing thing was the sauce tasted more like gravy rather than a good reduction. His 4th course was a Selection of Farmhouse and Artisanal Cheeses. A large cart was rolled out and he could choose 4 of them. This was still impressive. My favorite was the Fourme d'Ambert (a blue cheese from France)--it had a peppery aftertaste. I still love the Mignardise--9 bite-sized desserts. This was plenty for me and I'm glad we didn't order a dessert. If you're celebrating a special occasion, you get a bonus lemon cake. Before we left, a complimentary pumpkin muffin was delivered for the ladies--something to have the next day. I'm hoping this was just an off-night for them. The food was 4-star but Gary Danko lost another star for value. I expected more from a Michelin-starred restaurant. Will I go back? Yes Is it worth a drive? Yes 12/29/2013

Where do I begin??? My husband and I were in town for our anniversary and picked THE PERFECT RESTAURANT to celebrate a very special occassion. We had scoped this fine dining venue on Yelp and the reviews are true..ambience is dark and romantic, food portions are fairly generous (not to mention soooo tasty!) and service was impeccable. The menu is unique in which you are entitled to choose anywhere from 3-5 courses based on set prices (we both picked 4 each for $101) and can double up on the apperizers if you're not hungry or do the complete opposite and double up on the entrees (it's a lot of food!). We are total foodies and every single course was much-o deliciouso from beginning to end! We indulged in the following: Risotto Rock Shrimp, Seared Foie Gras, Pan Seared Bass, Coconut Thai Curry, Seared Filet, Grand Marnier Souffle, Baked Chocolate Soufflé and alas, mouth-watering desserts compliments of the chef! We were completely content and rolled out of Gary Danko's feeling happy and stuffed! Will return again some time in the near future!

Mouthgasm. It's an oral orgasm.. wait, that just doesn't sound right. 5 courses of pure, unadulterated flavor. Well, 8 if you count my friends' dishes that I got to sample, as well. -Amuse bouche - corn soup. Simple, but tasty. Okay so it's not any beter than the corn soups from Curry House down in LA that I grew up eating, but it's tasty nevertheless. -Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini and Lettuce Cream - Holy crap, I wasn't expecting that much caviar. 'Nuff said. -Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Peas, Corn and Roasted Tomatoes - Perfectly done risotto. Perfect texture. The sauce was just the right amount of richness, imho. -Seared Sonoma foie gras - MONEY!!! One of the best foies I've ever had! The marmalade (which, I believe, was kind of like balsamic onions) were the perfect accompaniment to the flavor of the foie. I'm going to be so sad when this goes off the menu next year.. DAMN CALIFORNIA HIPPIES! SAVE OUR FOIE! (okay, done ranting) -Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn and Tarragon - This was probably the weakest dish. I mean, it was still really good... but it didn't wow me as much as the others. Then again.. it's hard to follow the foie, huh? I think a more undercooked lobster would've been a bit better. -Herb Crusted Lamb Loin with Tian of Summer Vegetables and Polenta - Yum. Perfectly cooked lamb. However, I prefer a little bit more flavor in my lamb.. It tasted almost steak-like. Hardly any of that gamey taste. Wait, that's a good thing, right? It was kind of hard to taste the "herb crust" as well, since each slice was so thin.. but I guess the flavor is supposed to be suble; not overpowering. -Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Tomato-Corn Relish and Basil Butter - Great stuff. Perfectly cooked, and the sauces that flavored the beef were just.. perfect. -Trio of Créme Brulée with Assorted Cookies - Good.. but that lemon one tasted kind of like a mojito creeme brulee. Weird. -Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces - WOW. I could eat this every day! Service was good, as expected. Although.. I had periods where my wine glass was empty. After waiting for a while, I was saying, "Okay, my glass has been empty for a while so I'm just going to start pouring my own..." and just as I grabbed the bottle, the waitress ran over to pour it for me. Good save. I've been to way too many over-priced restaurants in SF where I felt leaving like it wasn't worth the money.. but damn, Gary Danko. TAKE MY MONEY! Pro Tip - Bring a good wine. Pay the $35 corkage. Your wallet will thank you for it.

We went to Gary Danko's on our fifth anniversary trip to San Francisco. I'm not a person who is always comfortable in really fancy restaurants, but I wanted to try the amazing food I had heard about, so I made a reservation. When we first got there, we had to wait quite a bit for our table. They never let us get upset, though, sending us free drinks and little bites "from the chef" that included a wonderful warm salmon on a crisp bread round, topped with caviar. Everyone from the bartender to the waiters, etc., kept walking up to us and apologizing profusely and offering to bring us something else on the house. They have a wonderful fixed price menu, where you can order the 3-, 4- or 5-course meal and get anything on the menu in it. We got the 5-course for around $90 each (we decided to splurge). My husband and I got something different for each course so we could try each other's food, and they were ALL amazing. One course after another was cooked perfectly and just amazing to taste. They portions were just right for five courses, which, for us, included a dessert and cheese course. The service was amazing from the first minute we sat down. I never felt uncomfortable or condescended to, as can happen in restaurants of this caliber. I felt comfortable asking questions about what certain items on the menu were, and the waiter knew all of the answers. Quite impressive! I think they were had spy cameras or something, because our empty plates never sat long in front of us, and it was clearly a well-oiled machine working to bring us utensils, etc., for the next course. At the end of the meal, they brought us a wonderful chocolate dessert with "Happy Anniversary" artfully written on the plate in chocolate. By this time, there weren't many people left eating, but we never felt rushed. After that, the waiter brought us a tray full of little dessert bites, telling us the chef had been experimenting with things and wanted us to try them on the house. We also were plied with muffins, wine bottle openers and other swag on our way out, the different employees *still* apologizing for how long we had to wait. Throughout the night, we were comped all of our drinks and quite a bit of food in what seemed an attempt to make up for our having to wait what, at most, was a half-hour wait. And hey, it worked! We were thrilled with our overall experience, and we have told everyone we know going out to San Francisco since then.

OMG! One of THE finest meals we've ever had. We definitely do it again. Pros: * Food - amazing and beautiful (see lengthy foodie comments below) * Service - exceedingly professional, knowledgeable, friendly & engaging * Cocktails - our Old Fashioned (one with Rye & the other with Woodford Reserve) were excellent. Cons: * While the Chocolate Soufflé has a great flavor, it was slightly undercooked and runny in the middle. But, the accompanying Crème Anglaise & Dark Chocolate Sauces were divine. * Wish they would consider a broader Craft Beer selection. Beer is hip now, and there are some amazing regional brews that would pair wonderfully with this top-notch food menu. ---- The Meal... NOTE: Everything was beautifully plated. Starters: * Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frisée and Pancetta - Perfectly poached egg and superbly flash-fried to achieve amazing balance of tender & crunchy with great complementary of flavors from the polenta & mushrooms. * Quail Salad with Rosemary Potato Cake, Maitake Mushrooms and Pomegranate - Wonderfully crisp brown glaze on the outside and tender & moist on the inside. The potato cake was the most astounding hash browns we've ever tried. The salad was simple and contrasted nicely. Fish: * Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Scallions and Shiitake Mushrooms - Better than most any Asian restaurant with super fresh and tender shellfish. The Curry sauce was shimmered like liquid gold and was incredibly smooth and flavorful. * Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon - The most beautifully plated of our dishes. The lobster, potato & mushrooms had delightfully subtle and complementary flavors. Entrées: * Herb Crusted Lamb Loin with Tian of Winter Vegetables and Polenta - Meat to cooked to a perfect medium rare. Marvelously rich polenta (could have been a meal onto itself) with beautifully tender Provencal-style vegetables. * Juniper Crusted Venison with Braised Red Cabbage, Cranberry Compote, Chestnut Spaetzle and Tangerines - Cooked to a melt-in-your-mouth medium rare. The juniper crusting was astounding and perfectly balanced. The cabbage & cranberry were good, but the Spaetzle took the prize of the side dishes with a delightful chestnut flavor and texture. Dessert: * Chocolate Praline Parfait with Bourbon Sauce and Salted Caramel Ice Cream - this was wonderfully sweet & salty, which kept from being overwhelming. It was so good, we almost fought for the last bite! What an amazing meal. YUM!

It really is as good as it gets. If you can't get a reservation... Try the bar!

    I'm so sad that I can't give Gary Danko a 5-star review. It used to be my favorite restaurant in SF.

    We went on a Sunday night. I had wanted a Saturday night but I forgot to call exactly 2 months prior and by the time I remembered, it was the day after and there was nothing available for the Saturday. I've heard that Sundays and Mondays are bad nights to have dinner out because the experienced kitchen & wait staff usually take those nights off and it appeared to be the case on our visit.

    We hit Golden Gate bridge traffic and arrived 15 minutes late. Within 5 minutes of our arrival, while we were still looking at our menu, the amuse bouche was delivered. I thought it was because we were late but it appeared to be the norm since all others in the dining room experienced the same. I balanced the menu on my lap while I had the Curried Carrot Soup with Cumin. This was way too salty and the cumin competed with the curry.

    I chose the 3-course dinner for $76 and started with Risotto with Lobster, Gulf Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms and Butternut Squash. It was truffle season and you could add 1 gram of shaved black truffle for $20 or 1 gram of shaved white truffle for $25. Based on our trip to the truffle festival in Alba, I knew that the white truffle was more flavorful so I went for it. The truffle looked beautiful but unfortunately there was no truffle smell or taste. It was disappointing. The risotto was well made and al dente though.

    My next course was the Branzini with Fennel Puree, Nicoise Olives and Saffron-Orange Emulsion. The Branzini was well made. The flesh was soft and the skin was crisp. The fennel puree had no fennel flavor though--it was more like green mashed potato. The saffron-orange emulsion was very mild and not memorable.

    My last course was Venison with Red Cabbage and Herb Spaetzle. The venison was dry but the cabbage did have good flavor.

    My husband had the 4-course dinner for $94. He started with Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing. The dressing was too tart--too much lemon.

    His fish course was the Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon. The lobster was perfectly cooked but there was not much flavor to it.

    His next course was Veal with Veal Sweetbread. My husband ordered the dish because he loves sweetbread but the sweetbread was a very small piece. The most disappointing thing was the sauce tasted more like gravy rather than a good reduction.

    His 4th course was a Selection of Farmhouse and Artisanal Cheeses. A large cart was rolled out and he could choose 4 of them. This was still impressive. My favorite was the Fourme d'Ambert (a blue cheese from France)--it had a peppery aftertaste.

    I still love the Mignardise--9 bite-sized desserts. This was plenty for me and I'm glad we didn't order a dessert. If you're celebrating a special occasion, you get a bonus lemon cake.

    Before we left, a complimentary pumpkin muffin was delivered for the ladies--something to have the next day.

    I'm hoping this was just an off-night for them. The food was 4-star but Gary Danko lost another star for value. I expected more from a Michelin-starred restaurant.

    Will I go back? Yes
    Is it worth a drive? Yes

We were completely content and rolled out of Gary Danko's feeling happy and stuffed! Will return again some time in the near future!

    1 check-in

    Mouthgasm. It's an oral orgasm.. wait, that just doesn't sound right.

    5 courses of pure, unadulterated flavor. Well, 8 if you count my friends' dishes that I got to sample, as well.

    -Amuse bouche - corn soup. Simple, but tasty. Okay so it's not any beter than the corn soups from Curry House down in LA that I grew up eating, but it's tasty nevertheless.

    -Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini and Lettuce Cream  - Holy crap, I wasn't expecting that much caviar. 'Nuff said.

    -Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Peas, Corn and Roasted Tomatoes - Perfectly done risotto. Perfect texture. The sauce was just the right amount of richness, imho.

    -Seared Sonoma foie gras - MONEY!!! One of the best foies I've ever had! The marmalade (which, I believe, was kind of like balsamic onions) were the perfect accompaniment to the flavor of the foie. I'm going to be so sad when this goes off the menu next year.. DAMN CALIFORNIA HIPPIES! SAVE OUR FOIE!

    (okay, done ranting)

    -Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn and Tarragon - This was probably the weakest dish. I mean, it was still really good... but it didn't wow me as much as the others. Then again.. it's hard to follow the foie, huh? I think a more undercooked lobster would've been a bit better.

    -Herb Crusted Lamb Loin with Tian of Summer Vegetables and Polenta - Yum. Perfectly cooked lamb. However, I prefer a little bit more flavor in my lamb.. It tasted almost steak-like. Hardly any of that gamey taste. Wait, that's a good thing, right? It was kind of hard to taste the "herb crust" as well, since each slice was so thin.. but I guess the flavor is supposed to be suble; not overpowering.

    -Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Tomato-Corn Relish and Basil Butter - Great stuff. Perfectly cooked, and the sauces that flavored the beef were just.. perfect.

    -Trio of Créme Brulée with Assorted Cookies - Good.. but that lemon one tasted kind of like a mojito creeme brulee. Weird.

    -Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces - WOW. I could eat this every day!

    Service was good, as expected. Although.. I had periods where my wine glass was empty. After waiting for a while, I was saying, "Okay, my glass has been empty for a while so I'm just going to start pouring my own..." and just as I grabbed the bottle, the waitress ran over to pour it for me. Good save.

    I've been to way too many over-priced restaurants in SF where I felt leaving like it wasn't worth the money.. but damn, Gary Danko. TAKE MY MONEY!

    Pro Tip - Bring a good wine. Pay the $35 corkage. Your wallet will thank you for it.

    3/1/2013

    We went to Gary Danko's on our fifth anniversary trip to San Francisco. I'm not a person who is always comfortable in really fancy restaurants, but I wanted to try the amazing food I had heard about, so I made a reservation.

    When we first got there, we had to wait quite a bit for our table. They never let us get upset, though, sending us free drinks and little bites "from the chef" that included a wonderful warm salmon on a crisp bread round, topped with caviar. Everyone from the bartender to the waiters, etc., kept walking up to us and apologizing profusely and offering to bring us something else on the house.

    They have a wonderful fixed price menu, where you can order the 3-, 4- or 5-course meal and get anything on the menu in it. We got the 5-course for around $90 each (we decided to splurge). My husband and I got something different for each course so we could try each other's food, and they were ALL amazing. One course after another was cooked perfectly and just amazing to taste. They portions were just right for five courses, which, for us, included a dessert and cheese course.

    The service was amazing from the first minute we sat down. I never felt uncomfortable or condescended to, as can happen in restaurants of this caliber. I felt comfortable asking questions about what certain items on the menu were, and the waiter knew all of the answers. Quite impressive! I think they were had spy cameras or something, because our empty plates never sat long in front of us, and it was clearly a well-oiled machine working to bring us utensils, etc., for the next course.

    At the end of the meal, they brought us a wonderful chocolate dessert with "Happy Anniversary" artfully written on the plate in chocolate. By this time, there weren't many people left eating, but we never felt rushed. After that, the waiter brought us a tray full of little dessert bites, telling us the chef had been experimenting with things and wanted us to try them on the house. We also were plied with muffins, wine bottle openers and other swag on our way out, the different employees *still* apologizing for how long we had to wait. Throughout the night, we were comped all of our drinks and quite a bit of food in what seemed an attempt to make up for our having to wait what, at most, was a half-hour wait. And hey, it worked! We were thrilled with our overall experience, and we have told everyone we know going out to San Francisco since then.

    2/1/2013

    1 check-in

    OMG!  One of THE finest meals we've ever had.  We definitely do it again.

    Pros:
    * Food - amazing and beautiful (see lengthy foodie comments below)
    * Service - exceedingly professional, knowledgeable, friendly & engaging
    * Cocktails - our Old Fashioned (one with Rye & the other with Woodford Reserve) were excellent.

    Cons:
    * While the Chocolate Soufflé has a great flavor, it was slightly undercooked and runny in the middle.  But, the accompanying Crème Anglaise & Dark Chocolate Sauces were divine.

    * Wish they would consider a broader Craft Beer selection.  Beer is hip now, and there are some amazing regional brews that would pair wonderfully with this top-notch food menu.  

    ----

    The Meal...  
    NOTE:  Everything was beautifully plated.

    Starters:
    * Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frisée and Pancetta -  Perfectly poached egg and superbly flash-fried to achieve amazing balance of tender & crunchy with great complementary of flavors from the polenta & mushrooms.

    * Quail Salad with Rosemary Potato Cake, Maitake Mushrooms and Pomegranate - Wonderfully crisp brown glaze on the outside and tender & moist on the inside.  The potato cake was the most astounding hash browns we've ever tried.  The salad was simple and contrasted nicely.

    Fish:
    * Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Scallions and Shiitake Mushrooms - Better than most any Asian restaurant with super fresh and tender shellfish.  The Curry sauce was shimmered like liquid gold and was incredibly smooth and flavorful.

    * Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon - The most beautifully plated of our dishes.  The lobster, potato & mushrooms had delightfully subtle and complementary flavors.

    Entrées:
    * Herb Crusted Lamb Loin with Tian of Winter Vegetables and Polenta - Meat to cooked to a perfect medium rare.  Marvelously rich polenta (could have been a meal onto itself) with beautifully tender Provencal-style vegetables.

    * Juniper Crusted Venison with Braised Red Cabbage, Cranberry Compote, Chestnut Spaetzle and Tangerines - Cooked to a melt-in-your-mouth medium rare. The juniper crusting was astounding and perfectly balanced.  The cabbage & cranberry were good, but the Spaetzle took the prize of the side dishes with a delightful chestnut flavor and texture.

    Dessert:
    * Chocolate Praline Parfait with Bourbon Sauce and Salted Caramel Ice Cream - this was wonderfully sweet & salty, which kept from being overwhelming.  It was so good, we almost fought for the last bite!

    What an amazing meal.  YUM!
